Although this is possible, `BigInteger` objects are [immutable][1] and I can&#39;t imagine a need to copy.

  [1]: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Immutable_object

Firstly, you shouldn&#39;t need to copy a `BigInteger` because it is immutable class.  (Copying a `BigInteger` is about as useful as copying a `String` ... )

But if you do need to copy one, then a more efficient way to do it would be this:

    BigInteger first = new BigInteger(42);
    BigInteger second = first.add(BigInteger.ZERO);

This avoids the (relatively) expensive binary -&gt; decimal -&gt; binary conversions and the creation of an intermediate string.

And `BigInteger.clone()` should be more efficient still ...

The immutability doesn&#39;t solve this problem:
Suppose you want to write a loop equivalent to

    int a = 10;
    for(int i = a; i &lt; 10; i++){...}

with BigIntegers.
The initial value in a will be needed later on:

    BigInteger a = new BigInteger(10);
    for(BigInteger i = a.copy(); a.compare(BigInteger.TEN) &lt; 0; i = i.plus(BigInteger.ONE)
    {...}

The initialization of the loop variable i will need a (nonexistent) copy operation,
since otherwise i and a would point to the same object and the value
in a would be lost once i is increased within the loop.

My best guess on an efficient way to do the copying would be something like

